1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,000
In this lesson we will learn more about query loops and using the Query Loop block.

2
00:00:06,000 --> 00:00:09,000
Let's first talk about the Query lLoop block.

3
00:00:09,000 --> 00:00:12,000
This powerful block can be used to display posts based on specified parameters.

4
00:00:14,000 --> 00:00:17,000
This is also the block that is used on your blog page to display all your posts

5
00:00:19,000 --> 00:00:22,000
and will allow you to ask the database to show you all the posts about a specific topic.

6
00:00:26,000 --> 00:00:29,000
For example, you can ask to see all the posts written about gluten free recipes.

7
00:00:33,000 --> 00:00:36,000
Or you might want to see posts about reviews of computer games.

8
00:00:39,000 --> 00:00:42,000
Each Query Loop block is made up of various blocks like the Post Featured block,

9
00:00:45,000 --> 00:00:48,000
the Categories block, the Post Title block, the Post Author block, the Post Excerpt block, etc.

10
00:00:55,000 --> 00:00:58,000
While you won't be able to edit the content of these nested blocks,

11
00:00:59,000 --> 00:01:02,000
you can customize the appearance and layout, including adding or removing additional blocks as you'd like.

12
00:01:06,000 --> 00:01:09,000
Let's look at a few example websites to see how they have used query loops.

13
00:01:12,000 --> 00:01:15,000
In our first example, a query loop has been used to highlight the latest stories,

14
00:01:17,000 --> 00:01:20,000
recognizing women's creativity, leadership, courage and innovation.

15
00:01:22,000 --> 00:01:25,000
And below that, a query loop has been used to display blog posts.

16
00:01:28,000 --> 00:01:31,000
In the second example, query loops have been used to display different types of recipes.

17
00:01:33,000 --> 00:01:36,000
First up, we have breakfast recipes, and if we scroll down, amazing appetizers.

18
00:01:41,000 --> 00:01:44,000
And in our last example, a query loop has been used to create a news page.

19
00:01:50,000 --> 00:01:53,000
Let's first look at how to modify a Query Loop block and to use patterns.

20
00:01:55,000 --> 00:01:58,000
So let's make our way to Appearance and click on Editor.

21
00:01:59,000 --> 00:02:02,000
This will take us to our Site Editor and currently we are on our blog home template,

22
00:02:05,000 --> 00:02:08,000
that displays all our blog posts.

23
00:02:11,000 --> 00:02:14,000
Let's open the list for you to see how our Query Loop block is structured.

24
00:02:17,000 --> 00:02:20,000
At the top, we will see the Featured Image block.

25
00:02:23,000 --> 00:02:26,000
Then we have the Post Title block followed by the Post Meta blocks.

26
00:02:34,000 --> 00:02:37,000
And they include the Post Date block, the Post Author block as well as the Categories block.

27
00:02:42,000 --> 00:02:45,000
And then lastly, the Post Excerpt block.

28
00:02:45,000 --> 00:02:48,000
But of course, we can alter what we want to have displayed.

29
00:02:49,000 --> 00:02:52,000
So let's for example, delete the Post Excerpt block.

30
00:02:54,000 --> 00:02:57,000
And then select the Post Title block and drag and drop it to above the Featured Image block.

31
00:03:03,000 --> 00:03:06,000
And the great thing about updating the Query Loop block is that if you change something in one post,

32
00:03:08,000 --> 00:03:11,000
it will appear everywhere else.

33
00:03:11,000 --> 00:03:14,000
But what if we want to use a completely different pattern and layout?

34
00:03:16,000 --> 00:03:19,000
Well, we can click on Replace in our block toolbar and browse through the various patterns that come with your theme.

35
00:03:24,000 --> 00:03:27,000
And when you select a pattern, you can of course customize it as you please.

36
00:03:32,000 --> 00:03:35,000
When you add a new Query Loop block, you will have two options.

37
00:03:37,000 --> 00:03:40,000
You can choose a pattern or you can start blank.

38
00:03:41,000 --> 00:03:44,000
When you click on Start blank, then you can select one of the variations.

39
00:03:45,000 --> 00:03:48,000
In this case, I will select Title, Date and Excerpt.

40
00:03:49,000 --> 00:03:52,000
And then we can modify it further.

41
00:03:51,000 --> 00:03:54,000
So let's go ahead and add a Featured Image block below the title.

42
00:04:03,000 --> 00:04:06,000
And then we can open up Styles and change the aspect ratio to for example, 4x3,

43
00:04:13,000 --> 00:04:16,000
to ensure that all the post featured images display the same.

44
00:04:21,000 --> 00:04:24,000
Next up, we are going to have a look at taxonomies or filters and how to use the sidebar settings.

45
00:04:27,000 --> 00:04:30,000
I've created a lifestyle page and only want to see posts related to this topic.

46
00:04:32,000 --> 00:04:35,000
So I will select the Query Loop block and then open up my sidebar settings.

47
00:04:40,000 --> 00:04:43,000
And the first thing we have to do is deselect Inherit query from template,

48
00:04:46,000 --> 00:04:49,000
as I want to customize the settings of the query loop.

49
00:04:51,000 --> 00:04:54,000
And when you scroll down, you now have an option to filter your posts by using taxonomies,

50
00:05:01,000 --> 00:05:04,000
such as categories and tags, authors and even keywords.

51
00:05:09,000 --> 00:05:12,000
I am going to select taxonomies as I've created a category called lifestyle

52
00:05:15,000 --> 00:05:18,000
and only want to see posts with this category displayed.

53
00:05:20,000 --> 00:05:23,000
And when I add the lifestyle category, all posts that don't have this category will be excluded.

54
00:05:29,000 --> 00:05:32,000
You also have the option to display posts from a specific author.

55
00:05:33,000 --> 00:05:36,000
So once I select the Query Loop block again, I will go to my sidebar settings,

56
00:05:39,000 --> 00:05:42,000
click on filters, select Authors and select the person whose posts I would like to display.

57
00:05:49,000 --> 00:05:52,000
Now we will only see posts written by Roger Lister.

58
00:05:58,000 --> 00:06:01,000
You can of course also choose a keyword and only display posts which contain that word or words in the text.

59
00:06:09,000 --> 00:06:12,000
Lastly, let's have a closer look at our sidebar settings.

60
00:06:13,000 --> 00:06:16,000
As mentioned, I've deselected Inherit query from the template to customize the query.

61
00:06:18,000 --> 00:06:21,000
If you toggle it on, certain customization options will be hidden.

62
00:06:22,000 --> 00:06:25,000
And if you toggle it off, more customization options will appear.

63
00:06:27,000 --> 00:06:30,000
When you add a new Query Loop block to a post or template, it is also important to turn this off as your Query Loop block might not appear on the front end.

64
00:06:38,000 --> 00:06:41,000
The next option is post type.

65
00:06:41,000 --> 00:06:44,000
At the moment we are displaying blog posts.

66
00:06:44,000 --> 00:06:47,000
But you can also display pages or even custom post types.

67
00:06:48,000 --> 00:06:51,000
Below that you have the option to order your posts from newest to oldest, oldest to newest or alphabetically.

68
00:06:56,000 --> 00:06:59,000
Next, let's talk about sticky posts.

69
00:06:59,000 --> 00:07:02,000
A sticky post is a post that sticks to the top of your blog page and the option in your sidebar settings will allow you to include sticky posts, exclude them or only show sticky posts.

70
00:07:10,000 --> 00:07:13,000
Below sticky posts, we will see the option to turn off Force page reload.

71
00:07:15,000 --> 00:07:18,000
And this will allow someone to browse through posts without a page reloading.

72
00:07:20,000 --> 00:07:23,000
And this could contribute to a better user experience.

73
00:07:24,000 --> 00:07:27,000
And finally, we have already discussed using filters.

74
00:07:29,000 --> 00:07:32,000
All the best as you take advantage of this powerful blog to display posts.

